metadata.name: Organicon, variation II #50
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
One of 128 unique generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation II is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: Complicare #60
metadata.description:
Complicare is my first "still" generative work, and an exercise in minimalism.

Inspired by pioneers like Sol Lewitt and Frank Stella, as well as current fx_hash artists such as Rev Dan Catt and Yazid, this work attempts to balance a diverse visual output with a restricted generative system. I also wanted to focus on honing my abilities to add texture to the digital canvas, taking cues from other great artists on here like William Mapan and Hevey.

Each piece has one of 17 different layouts and one of 6 different color palettes.

Thanks to all of the artists on fx_hash for inspiring me every day to make more art, and particularly to dcarcher for some really insightful artistic perspective and feedback.

metadata.name: Creta Sarculum #230
metadata.description:
An exploration of simple chalk rake designs. 

Each piece has a few key variables, probabilities for those variables are as follows:

75% Gradient Background
25% Solid Color Background
4.76% Each Chalk Color Palette (21 palettes)
50% Circular Modifier
25% Rectangular Modifier
15% Rectangular Gradient Modifier

Press 's' in Live View to save a full resolution image.

metadata.name: Smudge #3
metadata.description:
"Smudge" (2022) explores the potential for the digital to imitate the physical. 

A field of orthogonal lines is interrupted by a figure of smudged ink. 

What once was regarded as an error or imperfection within analogue drawing practices becomes a celebrated textural feature of coded imagery.

metadata.name: Happy Accidents #120
metadata.description:
Sometimes when you're working on your Creative Coding project, you make a change to the code and it breaks. But maybe that's a good thing. This project was created as a fun expression of what can happen if you allow yourself to go down the rabbit hole, and further break your code until you come up with a new idea.

Special thanks to @clayheaton and @sableRaph for the coding tips and tricks.

metadata.name: fxEinstein #49
metadata.description:
I have traditionally paid special attention to studying the biographies of great personalities. The more I was immersed in their lives, imagining myself in their shoes, the more often I met their eyes in my reflection.

I began to wonder, "What if?" What if one of my idols had been born in France or England, for example. Or maybe in Ukraine, or Italy... Most likely, it would have been a completely different person. Perhaps Albert Einstein from Italy would never have been able to change the modern understanding of Physics, but surely the hooligan glasses could have added color to his Italian personality. Or perhaps the smoking pipe? Suddenly the English Albert would become the detective who would later become the hero of Conan Doyle's novel... 

Then or now? Maybe he would have liked to walk around at home in a vest, and his fascination with music and rock concerts, where he and his friends threw a "horns" to a band performing, revealed Albert to the masses in a very different way.

Albert Einstein is a great man. His ideas and thoughts still haunt the public mind to this day. Excerpts from the ideas of one of the founders of theoretical physics do not lose their relevance even today. They could come from any image of Einstein.

KRCHR Â©

Self-taught artist. I love physics and mathematics. I love the world around me. I love studying it. To be honest, this work is special to me. As I said above, Albert Einstein is my idol.
